      <component>
        <section>
          <templateId root="2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.2.10"/>
          <code code="18776-5" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1" displayName="Plan of Treatment"/>
          <title>Plan of Care</title>
          <text>Multidisciplinary ALS care plan with quarterly visits coordinating neurology, pulmonology, nutrition, physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech-language pathology, social work, and palliative care. Diagnosis: clinically probable ALS by Awaji-Shima criteria, limb-onset (right arm), with secondary bulbar involvement at month 9. Family history: no known family history of ALS, MND, or FTD. C9orf72 testing: negative. Most recent ALSFRS-R total: 32 / 48 (bulbar 8, fine motor 6, gross motor 9, respiratory 9). ECAS administered at last visit: total 108 / 136 (ALS-specific 75, non-ALS-specific 33). No frontotemporal involvement noted. FVC: 62% predicted (down from 78% predicted three months ago). Started riluzole on 2023-06-01, tolerated well. Started edaravone on 2023-09-10. BiPAP (Trilogy 100) initiated on 2023-12-01 for nocturnal hypoventilation; transitioning to daytime use given ongoing FVC decline. CoughAssist (mechanical insufflator-exsufflator) added 2024-02-15 with twice-daily use. Suction machine and portable oxygen concentrator ordered through DME. PEG tube placed on 2024-01-11 without complication; using Joey feeding pump for overnight supplemental nutrition. AAC eval completed by SLP on 2024-03-20; trialing Tobii Dynavox with eye-gaze input prior to device prescription. PT consult for power wheelchair fitting scheduled for 2024-05-02; tilt-in-space and head-array control under evaluation. Hospital bed with alternating-pressure mattress, Hoyer lift, shower chair, and grab bars added to home DME order through OT consult. Continue current disease-modifying therapy and symptom management. Patient goals: maintain functional independence as long as possible through adaptive equipment and home modifications; manage symptoms (spasticity, sialorrhea, dysphagia, fatigue) to optimize quality of life; complete advance care planning including MOLST and discussion of long-term ventilation preferences. Voice banking initiated. Palliative care team engaged for symptom management and family support.</text>
